      <hr>
      <details>
        <summary>Abstract</summary>
        <article class=" has-text-justified"> The importance of energy to man can never be quantified, as
          energy provides the means
          by which man achieves his basic needs. In Nigeria as other African countries in sub- Sahara
          has little or no access to modern clean energy. Nigeria was ranked 187 out of 189 countries
          in terms of access to modern clean energy. This low access to modern clean energy in
          Nigeria necessitates the need to examine the likely determinants of energy poverty in the
          rural communities.
          The objective of the study is to examine the determinants of energy poverty in Nigerian
          rural communities.
          The study targeted some rural communities in Esan West Local Government of Edo State. A
          simple questionnaire was designed to elicit information from the respondents and the
          questionnaire was administered to 346 households selected using clustered sampling due to
          lack of sampling frame. The information collected was analysed with the use of Logistic
          regression techniques.
          The study has shown energy poverty decreases with education, occupation and access to
          more than one source of modern energy. It also showed that energy poverty increases with
          female headed household. The age and size of the households of such female contribute to
          being energy poor. It further reveals that old headed households may be energy poor.
          Lastly, status in the communities may decrease the likelihood of being energy poor.
          The study therefore recommends that there is need to increase household awareness on
          the health effect of traditional fuel because the finding showed that price of energy is
          relatively cheap in the communities. The study further recommends that energy consumed
          by female headed households should be subsidised.</article>
