      <details>
        <summary>Abstract</summary>
        <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> This study empirically investigates relationship between financial
          reporting quality and the
          corporate governance attributes of listed firms in Nigeria. Secondary data source which were
          extracted from the Annual reports and accounts of 50 sampled quoted companies that have
          fully adopted IFRS in the preparation of their financial statements from 2012 to date were used.
          A two stage data approach in which the first stage (pre-IFRS period from 2008-2011) was
          complemented by the second stage (post-IFRS period from 2011-2013) was adopted in carrying
          out the study. The survey research design which is a combination of both cross-sectional and
          time series design properties and panel data regression were also applied in order to achieve a
          satisfactory result. The findings revealed that, Boards’ independence is negatively related to
          financial reporting quality after the adoption of IFRS in Nigeria, while Board size and Audit
          committee independence are positively and significantly related to financial reporting quality in
          both the pre IFRS and post-IFRS adoption. And Board gender diversity is positively but
          insignificantly related with financial reporting quality in both the pre and post IFRS regime. It is
          recommended amongst others that companies should focus on determining the optimal board
          size to adopt, include a sufficient number of independent directors as part of the Board and
          ensuring that the majorities of directors on audit committee should be non-executive with
          financial and accounting expertise as well as increasing the female directors on the board in
          order to enhance high financial reporting quality of listed firms in Nigeria.</article>
