      <details>
        <summary>Abstract</summary>
        <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> This research work examined the effect of Monetary and Fiscal policies
          in controlling
          Unemployment in Nigeria. The study employed secondary sources of data sourced from Central
          Bank of Nigeria’s Statistical Bulletin, and were analyzed using Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test,
          Johansen Co-integration Test and Error Correction Model. The result of the unit root test
          revealed that all the macroeconomic variables are stationary at level while the co-integration
          test indicates that there is long run equilibrium relationship among the variables. The result of
          the Error Correction Model (ECM) revealed that government expenditure has negative
          significant effect on unemployment rate. Also, result indicates that interest rate has positive
          effect on unemployment rate while money supply has negative effect on unemployment rate in
          Nigeria. It thus concluded that the challenges of unemployment need adequate tackling for
          development and growth purpose. Based on findings it was recommended that; The monetary
          authority should from time to time liaise with government agencies in charge of government
          fiscal policy to see how their activities will be affected by fiscal policy measures and to
          incorporate both monetary and fiscal policy measures together so as to formulate and
          implement a viable policy that will reduce unemployment in the country. Another policy
          implication of this study is that interest rate should be reduced to the barest minimum to
          encourage local production while simultaneously focus attention on exchange rate policies in
          order to prevent leakages.</article>
      </details>
