        <summary>Abstract</summary>
        <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> Adequate funding is required for the development of Small and Medium
          Scale Enterprises
          (SMEs). Existing studies have concentrated on the benefits of funds to SMEs with little
          consideration on the issue of accessibility of such funds to the operators in Nigeria. Hence, the
          study investigated the factors limiting SMEs in accessing intervention funds set aside by the
          government through the banks.
          The objectives of the study are to evaluate the level of accessibility of government intervention
          funds by SMEs operators and examine the most limiting factors to the accessibility of such
          funds. The null hypothesis was that none of the banks’ lending requirement constitutes
          significance hindrance to government’s funds accessibility by SMEs operators.
          Data sourced with the aid of a well-structured questionnaire administered purposively on 400
          SMEs Operators in the study area. The data were analyzed using factor analysis, tables and
          percentages.
          Findings showed that the proportion of the intervention funds assessed annually was not up to
          15% of the available funds within the first five years of the funds’ take-off. Factor analysis
          results showed that financial reports and facility pricing, collateral securities and education of
          Operator, business sustainability requirements, experience of the owner manager and business
          plan were significant constraints to fund accessibility.
          The study concluded that, although sustainable sources of fund have been established for
          SMEs, limited numbers of operators have been able to access the funds due to the constraints
          highlighted above. There is need for government intervention in strategic awareness creation
          and training programme to educate the SMEs Operators on the banks’ requirements.</article>
